  "footnotes": [
    "Battle of Teutoburg Forest (9 CE): Arminius (Hermann), a Romanized Cherusci chieftain, lured three Roman legions under Varus into an ambush in the forests of northwestern Germany; the annihilation of ~20,000 soldiers permanently halted Roman expansion east of the Rhine — the single most consequential event in ancient Germanic history",
    "Holy Roman Empire (962–1806): Voltaire's famous quip that it was 'neither holy, nor Roman, nor an empire' captured its paradox — a decentralized federation of hundreds of sovereign territories united under an elected emperor; at its peak under the Hohenstaufen it rivaled any European power; by the late period it was effectively a legal framework rather than a state",
    "Golden Bull (1356): Emperor Charles IV's decree established the seven prince-electors (three archbishops + four secular rulers) who chose the emperor; it formalized the HRE's decentralized constitution and guaranteed the electors' sovereignty — cementing the fragmentation that would define German politics until Bismarck",
    "Thirty Years' War (1618–1648): beginning as a religious conflict in Bohemia, it engulfed all of Germany and killed approximately 8 million people (~30% of the German population); the Peace of Westphalia enshrined state sovereignty and religious tolerance but left Germany fragmented into ~300 sovereign territories",
    "Prussian rise (1640–1871): from a peripheral Brandenburg electorate, the Hohenzollern dynasty built a militarized state that became a European great power under Frederick the Great; Bismarck unified Germany through three wars (Denmark 1864, Austria 1866, France 1870–71), establishing the Kleindeutschland solution that excluded Austria",
    "Weimar Republic (1918–1933): Germany's first democracy was born in defeat and burdened by Versailles; despite cultural brilliance (Bauhaus, Einstein, Mann), it was undermined by hyperinflation, political extremism, and the Great Depression; Hitler's appointment as Chancellor (30 January 1933) and the Enabling Act ended democratic governance",
    "German division (1949–1990): the Cold War split produced two German states with radically different systems; West Germany's Wirtschaftswunder made it Europe's economic powerhouse, while East Germany became the most industrialized Soviet satellite; the Berlin Wall (1961–1989) became the iconic symbol of the Iron Curtain; reunification on 3 October 1990 was achieved through East German accession to the Federal Republic"
  ]
}
